1478":"1478","1511":"1511","1455":"1455","before 1480":"før 1480","1517":"1517","1526":"1526","Banbury, Oxford, England":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England","Banbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England"},"nl":{"1450–before 29 January 1494":"1450–vóór 29 januari 1494","1450–1494":"1450–1494","–1511":"–1511","1462–1526":"1462–1526","1480–1526":"1480–1526","1480–Female":"1480–Overleden","1481–Female":"1481–Overleden","1482–1517":"1482–1517","1437–1478":"1437–1478","–Female":"Overleden","about 1480":"circa 1480","about 1481":"circa 1481","1462":"1462","1450":"1450","1494":"1494","1482":"1482","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1437":"1437","before 29 January 1494":"vóór 29 januari 1494","1478":"1478","1511":"1511","1455":"1455","before 1480":"vóór 1480","1517":"1517","1526":"1526","Banbury, Oxford, England":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England","Banbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England"},"en":{"1450–before 29 January 1494":"1450–before 29 January 1494","1450–1494":"1450–1494","–1511":"–1511","1462–1526":"1462–1526","1480–1526":"1480–1526","1480–Female":"1480–Deceased","1481–Female":"1481–Deceased","1482–1517":"1482–1517","1437–1478":"1437–1478","–Female":"Deceased","about 1480":"about 1480","about 1481":"about 1481","1462":"1462","1450":"1450","1494":"1494","1482":"1482","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1437":"1437","before 29 January 1494":"before 29 January 1494","1478":"1478","1511":"1511","1455":"1455","before 1480":"before 1480","1517":"1517","1526":"1526","Banbury, Oxford, England":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England","Banbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Saunders","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Surrey and Kent): variant of   Sander  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Sander","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Erna, Erwin, Fritz, Manfred, Bernhard, Dieter, Franz, Gerda, Klaus, Wolfgang.","English (Cumberland), Dutch, German, and Swedish: from the personal name <i>Sander</i>, a shortened form of   Alexander  . Compare   Saunders  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived on sandy soil, from   Sand   1 + <i>-er</i>, suffix denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"Esq","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone living on or owning land that was waterlogged or partly surrounded by water, from Middle Low German <i>es</i> ‘swamp, water’.","Swiss German: from the topographic name <i>Ess</i> ‘grazing area, pasture’.","Swiss German: from a vernacular short form of the personal name   Oswald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Esse","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farmstead Ese in Sogn of unexplained etymology, or Esse in Telemark, named with Old Norse <i>æsin</i> ‘hill’ + <i>-e</i> from <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’.","German: variant of   Ess  , or a topographic name from the river name Esse in Hesse."]},{"name":"Oswald","meanings":["Scottish (Fife and Lanarkshire), northern English, German, and French (mainly Alsace and Lorraine): from an Old English personal name composed of the elements <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>weald</i> ‘power’. In the Middle English period, this fell together with the less common Old Norse cognate <i>Ásvaldr</i>. The name was introduced to Germany from England, as a result of the fame of Saint Oswald, a 7th-century king of Northumbria, whose deeds were reported by Celtic missionaries to southern Germany. The name was also borne by a 10th-century English saint of Danish parentage, who was important as a monastic reformer. Veneration of Saint Oswald, the king, spread from the German lands to the neighbouring Slavic lands as well. The surname in the (German) spelling <i>Oswald</i> is thus also found especially in Czechia and Slovakia, while in North America it also absorbed various Slavic forms (see 3 below).","Irish (Down): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> (see   Hussey   1).","Americanized form of Slovenian, Slovak, and Czech <b>Osvald</b>, Slovenian and Slovak <b>Ožvald</b> or <b>Ozvald</b>, and probably also of Slovenian <b>Ožbolt</b>: from vernacular forms of the German personal name <i>Oswald</i>, of Old English origin (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Saunders Esq was born in 1450, in Banbury, Oxfordshire, England as the son of William Saunders and Alice Olney. He had at least 4 daughters with Jane Spencer. He died before 29 January 1494, in his hometown."},"et":